lt"> Windows 8 Product Key Decoding
				</h2>
			=09


					=09
					=09
				<div class=3D"content">
					<div id=3D"post_message_639140">
						<blockquote class=3D"postcontent restore ">
							<b>NOTE</b>: All of the pkeys shown here are made up and invalid.<br=
>
<br>
<b><font size=3D"3">API For Pkey Verification</font></b><br>
<br>
You can change your pkey using "slui.exe 3".<br>
This program creates a COM interface. The DLL registered to this interface =
is sppcomapi.dll<br>
When sppcomapi.dll is verifying a pkey it loads pidgenx.dll and calls PidGe=
nX.<br>
Internally PidGenX calls PidGenX2.<br>
The prototype for PidGenX2 is shown below. All strings are null terminated.=
<br>
<br>
HRESULT WINAPI PidGenX2(IN const WCHAR* <b>pkey</b>,IN const WCHAR* <b>file=
</b>,IN const WCHAR* <b>number</b>,IN DWORD_PTR <b>unkown1</b>,IN DWORD_PTR=
 <b>unknown2</b>,OUT S30* <b>struct1</b>,OUT SA4* <b>struct2</b>,OUT S4F8* =
<b>struct3</b>);<b><br>
<br>
pkey</b>: 28 char product key with dashes. (example 4NGBK-JMWD8-X38C6-4J7J8=
-8GGGG)<b><br>
file</b>: Pkey config file to validate against. sppcomapi.dll will first tr=
y "C:\Windows\System32\spp\tokens\pkeyconfig\pkeycon  fig.xrm-ms" and if th=
e key is not valid it then tries "C:\Windows\System32\spp\tokens\pkeyconfig=
\pkeycon  fig-csvlk.xrm-ms".<b><br>
number</b>: I'm not sure what this is used for, but I don't believe it is u=
sed for validating the pkey. sppcompai.dll sets this to "05426".<b><br>
unknown1/unknown2</b>: I don't know what these parameters mean. They are bo=
th set to zero.<b><br>
struct1</b>: This structure is 0x30 bytes long. No initialization is needed=
.<b><br>
struct2</b>: This structure is 0xa4 bytes long. The first DWORD of this str=
ucture is its size. If this member is not set to 0xa4 the call will fail.<b=
><br>
struct3</b>: This structure is 0x4f8 bytes long. The first DWORD of this st=
ructure is its size. If this member is not set to 0x4f8 the call will fail.=
<br>
<br>
<b><font size=3D"3">Pkey Config File</font></b><br>
<br>
The first thing that PidGenX2 does is load the pkey config file. This is an=
 XML file that contains an XML document and a signed hash to verify the con=
tent. The verification process is nothing special. It is just annoying beca=
use when it loads the XML file into memory it changes it. You have to be su=
re you hash the modified version for verification not the version that is o=
n the disc. I haven't tried it, but you can probably use the CryptXML SDK t=
o verify it msdn.microsoft .com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/aa380252%28v=
=3Dvs.85%29.aspx#cryptxml_functions<br>
<br>
Inside of the &lt;tm:infoBin name=3D"pkeyConfigData"&gt; tag is a base64 en=
coded XML document. In this document there are three sections Configuration=
s, KeyRanges, and PublicKeys.<b><br>
<br>
Configurations</b>: The first important piece of information is the RefGrou=
pId this value is encoded into the pkey. Each RefGroupId corresponds to a A=
ctConfigId. The ActConfigId is used to help search through the KeyRanges se=
ction. The rest of the information here is self explainitory.<b><br>
KeyRanges</b>: Each ActConfigId is split into 1 or more key ranges. They ra=
nge between the Start and End. The position of a key in this range I call a=
 KeyId. The KeyId is encoded into the pkey.<b><br>
PublicKey</b>: I don't know what purpose this section serves. Most of the v=
alues are the base64 encoded text "msft:pkey/2009/cryptoprofile/hmac/sha256=
". However, I don't see any version of sha256 used in key verification. Thi=
s is probably related to the secret parameter.<br>
<br>
When PidGenX2 validates a key it uses the RefGroupId and searches through t=
he KeyRanges to make sure that the KeyId is valid. This also gives you lots=
 of info about the pkey. There are exactly 106,079,830,098 valid pkeys.<br>
<br>
<b><font size=3D"3">Debugging Tips</font></b><br>
<br>
Like many other binary files related to Windows licensing, pidgenx.dll is h=
eavily obfuscated. The code for many functions are encrypted into the binar=
y and they are dynamically decrypted and copied to memory. After the functi=
on is run the memory is freed. Luckily by using a debugger with hardware me=
mory read breakpoints this just becomes a nuisance. Some debuggers will cau=
se the program to crash. I suggest the debugger that comes with the Windows=
 DDK.<br>
<br>
Most of the encrypted functions are hand written assembly. Their function i=
s obfuscated and may require some analysis to figure out exactly what the c=
ode is doing. The code will often move memory around to try to make you los=
e track of it. It will even encrypt the memory pass it somewhere else and d=
ecrypt it.<br>
<br>
<b><font size=3D"3">Pkey Decoding</font></b><br>
<br>
<b>NOTE</b>: The functions are obfuscated and most of the code is superfluo=
us. I tried to simplify the code as much as possible. In doing so I may not=
 have accounted for an edge case. If you find a key that is not decoded pro=
perly let me know so I can fix the algorithm.<br>
<br>
<b>NOTE</b>: There is no error checking in my code to make it as simple as =
possible.<br>
<br>
<b>Step 1: Convert Characters</b><br>
Valid pkeys are of the form ?????-?????-?????-?????-?????<br>
Where ? may be any number of BCDFGHJKMPQRTVWXY2346789<br>
Note that the UI allows you to enter the character 5, but this is an invali=
d character.<br>
There must be one and only one N. The N must not be the last character.<br>
<br>
Each character matches a byte in a lookup table. The dashes are removed. Th=
e character N is removed. The zero based index of N is appended to the resu=
lt.<br>
<div class=3D"bbcode_container">
	<div class=3D"bbcode_description">Code:</div>
	<pre class=3D"bbcode_code" style=3D"height:434px;">void ConvertChars(WCHAR=
 key0[25],BYTE key1[25])
{
  UINT j=3D1;
  UINT i=3D0;
  while(j&lt;25)
  {
    switch(key0[i++])
    {
    case L'N':
      key1[0]=3Dj-1;
      break;
    case L'B':
      key1[j++]=3D0x00;
      break;
    case L'C':
      key1[j++]=3D0x01;
      break;
    case L'D':
      key1[j++]=3D0x02;
      break;
    case L'F':
      key1[j++]=3D0x03;
      break;
    case L'G':
      key1[j++]=3D0x04;
      break;
    case L'H':
      key1[j++]=3D0x05;
      break;
    case L'J':
      key1[j++]=3D0x06;
      break;
    case L'K':
      key1[j++]=3D0x07;
      break;
    case L'M':
      key1[j++]=3D0x08;
      break;
    case L'P':
      key1[j++]=3D0x09;
      break;
    case L'Q':
      key1[j++]=3D0x0a;
      break;
    case L'R':
      key1[j++]=3D0x0b;
      break;
    case L'T':
      key1[j++]=3D0x0c;
      break;
    case L'V':
      key1[j++]=3D0x0d;
      break;
    case L'W':
      key1[j++]=3D0x0e;
      break;
    case L'X':
      key1[j++]=3D0x0f;
      break;
    case L'Y':
      key1[j++]=3D0x10;
      break;
    case L'2':
      key1[j++]=3D0x11;
      break;
    case L'3':
      key1[j++]=3D0x12;
      break;
    case L'4':
      key1[j++]=3D0x13;
      break;
    case L'6':
      key1[j++]=3D0x14;
      break;
    case L'7':
      key1[j++]=3D0x15;
      break;
    case L'8':
      key1[j++]=3D0x16;
      break;
    case L'9':
      key1[j++]=3D0x17;
      break;
    case L'-':
    default:;
    }
  }
}</pre>
</div>Example:<br>
key0=3DJWNY3-GG8KP-GBFXR-P8HHH-67PK9<br>
key1=3D02 06 0e 10 12 04 04 16 07 09 04 00 03 0f 0b 09 16 05 05 05 14 15 09=
 07 17<br>
<br>
<b>Step 2: Decode</b><br>
This step produces all of the bits for information in a pkey. Although the =
bits are shuffled. This code uses the same optimization of checking for 0s =
that Microsoft's code uses, I kept because it doesn't complicate the code t=
oo much.<br>
<br>
After it has been decoded, the bits are stored as shown in this table.<br>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;"><b><font size=3D"5">----&gt;</font></b><=
a href=3D"https://web.archive.org/web/20120926182529/http://forums.mydigita=
llife.info/attachment.php?attachmentid=3D17720&amp;d=3D1348309649" title=3D=
"Name:  bits.png
Views: 251
Size:  13.8 KB">bits.png</a><b><font size=3D"5">&lt;----</font></b><br>
</div> <br>
<div class=3D"bbcode_container">
	<div class=3D"bbcode_description">Code:</div>
	<pre class=3D"bbcode_code" style=3D"height:378px;">void Decode(BYTE key1[2=
5],BYTE key2[16])
{
  UINT ikey=3D0;
  for(;ikey&lt;25;++ikey)
    if(key1[ikey]!=3D0)
      break;

  UINT nloop=3D0;
  UINT val;
  UINT outi;
  for(;ikey&lt;25;++ikey)
  {
    val=3Dkey1[ikey];
    for(UINT i=3D0;i&lt;nloop;++i)
    {
      outi=3Dkey2[i];
      val=3D(outi &lt;&lt; 4)+(outi &lt;&lt; 3)+val;
      key2[i]=3Dval;
      val =3D val &gt;&gt; 8;
    }
    if(val!=3D0)
      key2[nloop++]=3Dval;
  }
  key2[14]|=3D0x08;
}</pre>
</div>Example:<br>
